rn community and its residents. Drawing on decades of research, Patricia McCormack argues that Fort Chipewyan was never an isolated Aboriginal community but a plural society at the crossroads of global, national, and local forces. The steps that led Aboriginal people to sign Treaty No. 8 and accept scrip in 1899 and their struggle to maintain autonomy thereafter reveal that Aboriginal peoples and others can become modern without relinquishing cherished beliefs and practices. This study of the most famous of the Treaty No. 8 communities not only provides a window into the history of Canada and Alberta � it challenges the nature of history writing in Canada itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481670040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774816700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774816700/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles